Package org.neo4j.kernel.impl.api.index

Class TentativeConstraintIndexProxy

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.neo4j.kernel.impl.api.index.AbstractDelegatingIndexProxy
      • org.neo4j.kernel.impl.api.index.TentativeConstraintIndexProxy
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    IndexConfigProvider, MinimalIndexAccessor, IndexProxy
    public class TentativeConstraintIndexProxy
extends AbstractDelegatingIndexProxy
    What is a tentative constraint index proxy? Well, the way we build uniqueness constraints is as follows:
    1. Begin a transaction T, which will be the "parent" transaction in this process
    2. Execute a mini transaction Tt which will create the index rule to start the index population
    3. In T: Sit and wait for the index to be built
    4. In T: Create the constraint rule and connect the two
    The fully populated index flips to a tentative index. The reason for that is to guard for incoming transactions that gets applied. Such incoming transactions have potentially been verified on another instance with a slightly dated view of the schema and has furthermore made it through some additional checks on this instance since transaction T hasn't yet fully committed. Transaction data gets applied to the neo store first and the index second, so at the point where the applying transaction sees that it violates the constraint it has already modified the store and cannot back out. However the constraint transaction T can. So a violated constraint while in tentative mode does not fail the transaction violating the constraint, but keeps the failure around and will eventually fail T instead.
